        },
        {
          "id": "tech-5",
          "title": "The ultimate guide to /goal",
          "link": "https://x.com/Saboo_Shubham_/status/2054988166541770782",
          "source": "X",
          "tags": [
            "ai",
            "agents",
            "devtools"
          ],
          "description": "/goal is becoming a primitive for coding agents. The feature gives coding workers jobs with a defined done state. With /goal, users write down what 'done' looks like, and agents work towards it until it gets there. The feature appeared in OpenAI's Codex CLI a few weeks ago, and Claude Code just added it this week.",
          "one-liner": "The `/goal` feature, which defines a \"done state\" for coding agents to work towards, has been integrated into OpenAI's Codex CLI and Claude Code.",
          "summary": {
            "what": "The `/goal` primitive, now in OpenAI's Codex CLI and Claude Code, allows users to define a specific \"done state\" for coding agents. Agents then work towards this defined state until the task is complete, functioning as a job with a clear objective.",
            "why": "This signals a critical development in AI agent capabilities, moving from simple command execution to goal-oriented task completion, enhancing their utility for developers by providing a more structured and autonomous approach to coding tasks.",
            "takeaway": "If you use OpenAI's Codex CLI or Claude Code, experiment with the `/goal` feature to define clear objectives for your coding agents."
          },
          "decoder": "* **Primitive (in programming)**: A fundamental, basic building block or operation that cannot be broken down into simpler parts within a given system.\n* **Coding agents**: AI systems designed to assist or autonomously perform programming tasks, such as writing code, debugging, or refactoring.\n* **OpenAI's Codex CLI**: A command-line interface tool that provides access to OpenAI's Codex model, which can translate natural language into code.\n* **Claude Code**: A coding-focused version or feature of Anthropic's Claude AI model.",
          "rating": 4
        },
        {
          "id": "tech-6",
          "title": "fate (GitHub Repo)",
          "link": "https://github.com/nkzw-tech/fate",
          "image": "https://opengraph.githubassets.com/506455abf905cc9bb5d0a12c248d97a5433a632cd4e76c6c24d8aa149faddb29/nkzw-tech/fate",
          "source": "GitHub",
          "tags": [
            "frontend",
            "react",
            "data"
          ],
          "description": "fate is a data client for React that combines view composition, normalized caching, data masking, Async React features, and type-safe data fetching. It is designed to make data fetching and state management in React applications more composable, declarative, and predictable. The framework is just JavaScript and has a minimal API and no DSL. fate helps developers avoid overfetching, stop passing unnecessary data down the tree, and eliminate boilerplate types secreted solely for passing server data to child components.",
          "one-liner": "fate is a new React data client inspired by Relay and GraphQL, offering view composition, normalized caching, data masking, and type-safe data fetching with a minimal API.",
          "summary": {
            "what": "fate is an alpha-stage data client for React (requiring React 19.2+) that focuses on composable, declarative, and predictable data fetching. It uses co-located \"views\" for components to declare data requirements, features a normalized cache, data masking, and integrates Async React features like Suspense, aiming to reduce overfetching and boilerplate.",
            "why": "This project attempts to bring the sophisticated data management ergonomics of GraphQL frameworks like Relay to plain TypeScript and RPC backends, addressing a common pain point for React developers who desire similar benefits without adopting a full GraphQL stack.",
            "takeaway": "If you are a React developer working with React 19.2+ and looking for advanced data fetching and state management similar to Relay/GraphQL but using plain TypeScript and RPC, consider exploring the `fate` GitHub repository and its templates for a potential future solution."
          },
          "deep-summary": "* fate is a modern data client for React, inspired by Relay and GraphQL, designed for composable, declarative, and predictable data fetching and state management.\n* It combines view composition, a normalized cache, data masking, Async React features (Actions, Suspense, use), and type-safe data fetching.\n* Components declare their data requirements using co-located \"views,\" which are then composed into a single network request per screen to minimize requests and eliminate waterfalls.\n* The framework maintains a normalized cache, enabling efficient data updates, optimistic updates for mutations, and live view updates via Server-Sent Events.\n* fate enforces strict data selection for each view and masks (hides) data not explicitly requested, preventing accidental coupling and reducing overfetching.\n* It is built with just JavaScript, has a minimal API, and no DSL, distinguishing itself from GraphQL which requires its own type system and query language.\n* The project aims to provide GraphQL/Relay ergonomics (fragments co-located with components, normalized cache, compiler for hoisting fragments) for developers using tRPC or other type-safe RPC frameworks.\n* fate requires React 19.2+ and is currently in alpha, not production-ready.\n* Developers can start with `vp create fate my-app` using templates for Void app with Drizzle, tRPC with Drizzle, or tRPC with Prisma.",
          "decoder": "* **Relay**: A JavaScript framework for building data-driven React applications, developed by Facebook, that uses GraphQL for data fetching.\n* **GraphQL**: A query language for APIs and a runtime for fulfilling those queries with your existing data.\n* **Normalized cache**: A data caching strategy where each unique entity (e.g., a `User` or `Post`) is stored once in a single, consistent location, and references to these entities are used throughout the application. This prevents data duplication and simplifies updates.\n* **Data masking**: In the context of `fate`, it refers to the practice of preventing components from accessing data fields that they did not explicitly request in their view definition.\n* **Async React features**: Modern features in React, such as `Suspense` and `use`, that facilitate asynchronous operations and concurrent rendering, allowing components to \"suspend\" rendering while waiting for data or other async work.\n* **DSL (Domain-Specific Language)**: A specialized computer language designed for a particular application domain.\n* **tRPC**: A TypeScript framework for building end-to-end type-safe APIs without GraphQL or REST.",
          "rating": 4,
          "content-template-path": "full-content/2026-05-15/tech-6"
        },
        {
          "id": "tech-7",
          "title": "The great memory panic of 2026",
          "link": "https://asymco.com/2026/05/11/the-great-memory-panic-of-2026/",
          "image": "https://asymco.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/08-margins.png",
          "source": "Asymco",
          "tags": [
            "hardware",
            "enterprise",
            "supply-chain",
            "apple"
          ],
          "description": "Memory prices could move from 15% to 40% of the bill of materials for Apple devices. Apple operates at an enormous scale, and each of its products consumes some memory. When dealing with this kind of scale, there's usually a couple of years of lead time. The spike in demand for memory has disrupted this pipeline. Apple still has a lot of room to negotiate price, and the whole situation could end up with Apple gaining a lot of market share.",
          "one-liner": "Apple could exploit a projected 2026 memory shortage, pushing device bill of materials from 15% to 40% for rivals, potentially eliminating marginal competitors and increasing its market share.",
          "summary": {
