          "title": "The thinking was never just mine",
          "link": "https://uxdesign.cc/the-thinking-was-never-just-mine-9b73cc04c837",
          "source": "UXdesign.cc",
          "tags": [
            "ai",
            "research",
            "philosophy"
          ],
          "description": "AI tools like Anthropic's Claude can function more like rapid iteration partners than answer machines, helping people explore and refine ideas far faster than they could alone. Creativity has likely always been shaped by outside influences — conversations, books, criticism, memories, and culture — but AI makes that process unusually visible through prompts and chat histories. What ultimately makes an idea feel “yours” may not be pure originality, but the judgment behind it: the consistent pattern of choices, refinements, rejections, and instincts that shape the final outcome.",
          "one-liner": "AI tools like Anthropic's Claude are reframing human creativity by acting as rapid iteration partners, making the collaborative nature of idea generation unusually visible.",
          "summary": {
            "what": "The article explores how AI tools, specifically Anthropic's Claude, function as \"rapid iteration partners\" that help individuals explore and refine ideas more quickly than working alone. It suggests that creativity has always been influenced by external factors, but AI makes this process transparent through chat histories, shifting the perception of originality towards the judgment and choices that shape an outcome.",
            "why": "This offers an philosophical insight into the evolving relationship between human creativity and AI, suggesting that AI is not just a tool for automation but a new form of collaborative partner that challenges traditional notions of individual authorship and the creative process."
          },
          "rating": 3
        },
